07064nam a22009135i 9781800108257DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818001082577 a10.1515/97818001082572doi  a(DE-B1597)677231  a(OCoLC)1419788987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0240102bisacsh00aRenaissance Papers 2021 /ced. by William Given, Ward J. Risvold, Jim Pearce.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2022] 1bCamden House, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (170 p.) :b18 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRenaissance Papers ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t“Strange Serious Wantoning”: Early Modern Chess Manuals and the Ethics of Virtuous Subterfuge -- t“Both Use and Art”: Motifs and Method in Astrophil and Stella -- tEmbodied Love(rs): Injury and Comedy in Mary Wroth’s Urania -- tEdmund Spenser’s Automaton Alchemy: The Case of False Florimell -- tWho Edited the 1571 Mirror for Magistrates? -- tStatues Living and Conscious: Hermetic Statue-Magic in The Winter’s Tale -- tTransmutation and Refinement: The Metaphysics of Conversion and Alchemy in Renaissance Spain -- tThe Twelve Inka and the Twelve Caesars: Reflections on an Early Modern Visual Theme in the Art of Colonial Peru -- tLinguistics and Epistemology in Thomas Harriot’s North Atlantic World -- tAssembling the King’s Body: Examining Holbein’s Portrait Techniques and the Fashioning of Henry VIII’s Image in the English Renaissance -- tMolière’s L’École des Femmes between Shame and Guilt0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays on a wide range of topics including the role of early modern chess in upholding Aristotelian virtue; readings of Sidney, Wroth, Spenser, and Shakespeare; and several topics involving the New World.Renaissance Papers collects the best scholarly essays submitted each year to the Southeastern Renaissance Conference. The present volume opens with an essay on early modern chess, arguing that it covertly upheld an Aristotelian concept of virtue against the destabilizing ethical views of writers such as Machiavelli. This provocative opening is followed by iconoclastic discussions of Sidney's Astrophil and Stella, Wroth's Urania, and Spenser's Fairie Queen. The next essay investigates the mystery surrounding editorship of the 1571 printing of The Mirror for Magistrates. The essays then pivot into the exotic world of Hermetic "statue magic" in Shakespeare's Winter's Tale and the even more exotic worlds of alchemy, Aztec war gods, and conversion in sixteenth-century Mexico. Two further essays remain in the New World, the first examining the representational connections between the twelve Caesars and the twelve Inca kings, the second taking stock of Thomas Harriot's contribution to the understanding of Amerindian languages. The penultimate essay looks at Holbein's depiction of Henry VIII's ailing body, and the volume concludes with a complex analysis of guilt and shame in Molière's L'École des Femmes.Contributors: Jean Marie Christensen, William Coulter, Christopher Crosbie, Shepherd Aaron Ellis, Scott Lucas, Fernando Martinez-Periset, Timothy Pyles, Rachel Roberts, Jesse Russell, Janet Stephens, Weiao Xing. The journal is edited by Jim Pearce of North Carolina Central University and Ward Risvold of Georgia College and State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturevCongressesxHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aRenaissancevCongresses. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 16th Century .2bisacsh  aAstrophil and Stella.  aEdmund Spenser.  aHolbein.  aL'École des F